        "title": "Sibbecai and Elhanan — ordinary warriors finishing giant-class enemies",
        "range": "20:4-5",
        "excerpt": "Sibbecai the Hushathite killed Sippai, one of the descendants of the giants, and they were subdued. And there was war with the Philistines again, and Elhanan the son of Jair killed Lahmi the brother of Goliath the Gittite.",
        "body": "The transition from Ammon to Philistia is introduced by the Chronicler's standard formula: 'Now it came about after this' (20:4). The three Philistine vignettes that follow are abbreviated — each a few words — but each packs enormous theological density into its brevity. The first two (20:4-5) feature named but relatively obscure warriors dispatching named but enormous opponents.\n\nSibbecai the Hushathite (20:4) is identifiable from 1 Chronicles 11:29 as one of David's thirty mighty men, but he is not among the most celebrated of that elite corps. He kills Sippai — otherwise unknown — who is identified specifically as 'one of the descendants of the giants' (*yalid haraphah*, literally 'one born of Rapha'). The result is that 'the Philistines were subdued' (*kana*). That verb carries more than military connotation; in Chronicles it is a covenant word. God promised David in 1 Chronicles 17:10 that He would 'subdue all your enemies' — and the same root (*kana*) marks the fulfillment. Sibbecai's kill is not just a battlefield success; it is a covenant promise being kept in real time.\n\nElhanan son of Jair (20:5) presents the chapter's most complex textual issue. In 2 Samuel 21:19 (likely a scribal corruption), Elhanan son of Jaaregorgim is said to have killed Goliath himself — which contradicts 1 Samuel 17's famous account. Chronicles resolves the tension clearly: Elhanan kills 'Lahmi the brother of Goliath the Gittite.' The shaft of Lahmi's spear is described as 'like a weaver's beam' — the same description given for Goliath's own spear in 1 Samuel 17:7. The deliberate echo signals to the reader: this is a Goliath-class opponent. Goliath's dynasty has a weapon tradition; it also has an end. Elhanan provides the end.\n\nThe theological trajectory these two vignettes establish is crucial for reading the third. God's pattern is consistent: He appoints ordinary servants to defeat extraordinary enemies. The disciples of the Davidic court — formed under a king after God's own heart — carry something into battle that giant lineage cannot match.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yalid haraphah* (descendant of the giants, 20:4, 6) — literally 'born of Rapha'; the Rephaim are the ancient giant clans whose first appearances are in Genesis 14:5 and Deuteronomy 2:11. *Kana* (subdued, 20:4) — the covenant verb of enemy-humiliation; same root as 1 Chr 17:10. *Manor* (weaver's beam, 20:5) — the same weapon-description used for Goliath's spear in 1 Samuel 17:7, making the comparison unmistakable."
